{
  "What are the two primary pollutants that cause acid rain?": "",
  "Methane and carbon dioxide": "",
  "Sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides": "",
  "Carbon monoxide and ozone": "",
  "Lead and mercury": "",
  "Acid rain is primarily caused by sulfur dioxide (SO₂) and nitrogen oxides (NOₓ) that react with water vapor in the atmosphere to form sulfuric acid and nitric acid.": "",
  "What is the approximate pH of normal, unpolluted rainwater?": "",
  "5.6": "",
  "4.2": "",
  "7.0": "",
  "6.8": "",
  "Normal rainwater has a pH of about 5.6 because dissolved carbon dioxide from the atmosphere forms weak carbonic acid, making it naturally slightly acidic.": "",
  "Which human activity is the largest source of sulfur dioxide emissions that contribute to acid rain?": "",
  "Agriculture": "",
  "Deforestation": "",
  "Burning of coal in power plants": "",
  "Residential heating": "",
  "Coal-burning power plants are the largest anthropogenic source of sulfur dioxide because coal contains significant amounts of sulfur that is released as SO₂ when burned.": "",
  "What effect does acid rain have on aquatic ecosystems?": "",
  "It has no significant effect on water chemistry": "",
  "It promotes the growth of fish populations": "",
  "It increases biodiversity in lakes": "",
  "It lowers the pH of water bodies, harming aquatic organisms": "",
  "Acid rain lowers the pH of lakes and streams, which can kill fish, amphibians, and other aquatic organisms that are sensitive to acidic conditions, reducing biodiversity.": "",
  "What term describes the form of acid deposition that includes acidic fog, snow, and dry particles?": "",
  "Acid deposition": "",
  "Atmospheric condensation": "",
  "Chemical weathering": "",
  "Wet deposition only": "",
  "Acid deposition is the broader term that encompasses both wet deposition (rain, snow, fog) and dry deposition (acidic particles and gases settling on surfaces).": "",
  "How does acid rain affect soil chemistry?": "",
  "It increases the soil's water-holding capacity": "",
  "It has no measurable effect on soil": "",
  "It leaches essential nutrients and releases toxic aluminum": "",
  "It enriches soil with beneficial nutrients": "",
  "Acid rain leaches calcium, magnesium, and potassium from soil while dissolving aluminum from soil minerals, which is toxic to plant roots and can enter waterways.": "",
  "What U.S. legislation was specifically designed to reduce acid rain by targeting SO₂ and NOₓ emissions?": "",
  "National Environmental Policy Act": "",
  "Endangered Species Act": "",
  "Clean Water Act": "",
  "Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990": "",
  "The Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 established the Acid Rain Program, which created a cap-and-trade system for sulfur dioxide emissions and set limits on nitrogen oxide emissions.": "",
  "What type of rock is most vulnerable to damage from acid rain?": "",
  "Limestone and marble": "",
  "Granite": "",
  "Basalt": "",
  "Quartzite": "",
  "Limestone and marble are composed of calcium carbonate, which reacts readily with acids, making buildings and statues made of these materials especially vulnerable to acid rain erosion.": "",
  "Acid rain is considered a transboundary pollution problem because it can:": "",
  "Only affect the area where pollutants are emitted": "",
  "Travel hundreds of miles in the atmosphere before falling": "",
  "Only form over ocean water": "",
  "Be neutralized before crossing borders": "",
  "Prevailing winds can carry SO₂ and NOₓ hundreds or even thousands of miles from their source, causing acid rain to fall in regions far from where the pollutants were originally emitted.": "",
  "What technology is commonly used in coal-burning power plants to reduce sulfur dioxide emissions?": "",
  "Carbon capture systems": "",
  "Scrubbers (flue-gas desulfurization)": "",
  "Catalytic converters": "",
  "Electrostatic precipitators": "",
  "Scrubbers, or flue-gas desulfurization systems, use a limestone slurry to chemically react with and remove sulfur dioxide from power plant exhaust gases before they enter the atmosphere.": "",
  "What is acid rain?": "",
  "Rain contaminated with heavy metals from mining operations": "",
  "Rain with a pH above 7.0 caused by industrial emissions": "",
  "Any rainfall that contains dissolved minerals": "",
  "Precipitation with a pH below 5.6 caused by atmospheric reactions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides with water": "",
  "Acid rain refers to precipitation with a pH below 5.6 that forms when sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides in the atmosphere react with water vapor to produce sulfuric acid and nitric acid.": "",
  "What does the term 'wet deposition' mean in the context of acid rain?": "",
  "The settling of dry acidic particles on surfaces": "",
  "The absorption of pollutants by plant leaves": "",
  "The runoff of acidic water into streams": "",
  "The delivery of acids to Earth's surface through rain, snow, sleet, or fog": "",
  "Wet deposition refers to the process by which acidic compounds are dissolved in precipitation such as rain, snow, sleet, or fog and are deposited on the Earth's surface in liquid form.": "",
  "What is dry deposition?": "",
  "The formation of acid crystals in the upper atmosphere": "",
  "The evaporation of acidic water from lakes": "",
  "Acid rain that falls in desert regions": "",
  "The process where acidic gases and particles settle on surfaces without precipitation": "",
  "Dry deposition occurs when acidic gases and particles, such as SO₂ and sulfate particles, settle directly onto surfaces like buildings, trees, and soil without being dissolved in precipitation.": "",
  "What does 'buffering capacity' mean in relation to acid rain and water bodies?": "",
  "The speed at which acid rain flows into a lake": "",
  "The amount of rainfall a watershed can absorb": "",
  "The capacity of fish to tolerate acidic water": "",
  "The ability of a water body to resist changes in pH due to dissolved minerals": "",
  "Buffering capacity refers to a water body's ability to neutralize added acids, typically through dissolved calcium carbonate or bicarbonate from surrounding limestone bedrock that acts as a natural buffer.": "",
  "What is the pH scale?": "",
  "A logarithmic scale from 0 to 14 measuring the hydrogen ion concentration of a solution": "",
  "A scale measuring the oxygen content of water": "",
  "A ranking system for water quality standards": "",
  "A linear scale from 1 to 10 measuring water temperature": "",
  "The pH scale is a logarithmic scale ranging from 0 to 14 that measures the concentration of hydrogen ions in a solution, where each whole number change represents a tenfold change in acidity.": "",
  "What does 'liming' mean as a strategy for dealing with acid rain?": "",
  "Planting lime trees around acidified areas": "",
  "Adding calcium carbonate (limestone) to lakes or soil to neutralize acidity": "",
  "Applying a chemical coating to buildings to prevent erosion": "",
  "Filtering acid from rainwater before it reaches the ground": "",
  "Liming involves adding powdered limestone (calcium carbonate) to acidified lakes, rivers, or soils to raise the pH and neutralize the effects of acid deposition, restoring healthier conditions.": "",
  "What is a cap-and-trade system in the context of acid rain regulation?": "",
  "A system where the government directly controls factory operations": "",
  "A market-based approach that sets an overall emission limit and allows companies to buy and sell emission allowances": "",
  "A program that bans all sulfur emissions": "",
  "A tax placed on imported coal": "",
  "A cap-and-trade system sets a maximum total emission level (the cap) and distributes allowances that companies can trade, creating an economic incentive to reduce emissions below their allotment.": "",
  "What does 'chemical weathering' mean?": "",
  "The deposition of new minerals onto rock surfaces": "",
  "The formation of soil from volcanic ash": "",
  "The breakdown of rock and minerals through chemical reactions, often accelerated by acid rain": "",
  "The physical breaking apart of rock by wind and water": "",
  "Chemical weathering is the decomposition of rocks through chemical reactions with substances such as acids. Acid rain accelerates this process by reacting with minerals like calcium carbonate in limestone.": "",
  "What is flue-gas desulfurization?": "",
  "A technology that removes sulfur dioxide from the exhaust of fossil fuel power plants using chemical reagents": "",
  "A natural process where volcanoes absorb sulfur": "",
  "A process that converts sulfur into a fuel source": "",
  "A method of removing nitrogen from exhaust gases": "",
  "Flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) is a set of technologies used to remove sulfur dioxide from the exhaust flue gases of power plants, typically using a wet scrubber with a limestone slurry.": "",
  "What does 'acid shock' refer to in aquatic ecosystems?": "",
  "The gradual acidification of ocean water over centuries": "",
  "The natural buffering process in alkaline lakes": "",
  "A sudden, dramatic drop in pH of a water body, often during spring snowmelt, that can cause mass fish kills": "",
  "An increase in pH caused by algal blooms": "",
  "Acid shock occurs when accumulated acids stored in winter snowpack are rapidly released during spring snowmelt, causing a sudden and severe drop in the pH of streams and lakes that can be lethal to aquatic life.": "",
  "A national park in the Adirondack Mountains reports that several high-elevation lakes now have pH levels below 5.0 and have lost most of their fish populations. The region has granite bedrock. What best explains why these lakes are so severely affected by acid rain?": "",
  "Fish populations declined due to overfishing, not water chemistry": "",
  "Granite bedrock provides very little buffering capacity, so the lakes cannot neutralize the incoming acids": "",
  "High-elevation lakes receive less precipitation than lowland areas": "",
  "The lakes are too deep for acid rain to affect them": "",
  "Granite is a silicate rock that does not dissolve to release alkaline minerals, so lakes in granite watersheds have very low buffering capacity and cannot neutralize the sulfuric and nitric acids from acid deposition.": "",
  "A city notices that the marble facades of its historic buildings have become pitted and eroded over the past several decades. Air quality data shows elevated levels of SO₂ from nearby industrial sources. What is the most likely cause of the building damage?": "",
  "Acid deposition reacting with the calcium carbonate in the marble": "",
  "Physical weathering from wind-blown sand particles": "",
  "Ultraviolet radiation from the sun breaking down the marble": "",
  "Rising groundwater levels dissolving the building foundations": "",
  "Sulfur dioxide in the atmosphere forms sulfuric acid that reacts with the calcium carbonate in marble, converting it to calcium sulfate (gite gypsum), which is water-soluble and washes away, causing pitting and erosion.": "",
  "A coal-fired power plant in Ohio installs wet scrubbers that reduce SO₂ emissions by 90%. However, lakes in downwind New England states still show signs of acidification. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "The lakes are naturally acidic regardless of pollution": "",
  "Multiple pollution sources contribute to acid deposition, and nitrogen oxides from vehicles also play a significant role": "",
  "Scrubbers actually increase the acidity of emissions": "",
  "Acid rain only comes from local sources, not distant ones": "",
  "While reducing SO₂ from one source helps, acid rain results from multiple sources. Nitrogen oxides from vehicle exhaust and other power plants also form nitric acid, contributing to ongoing acidification.": "",
  "A Scandinavian country experiences severe acid rain damage despite having very few heavy industries of its own. Most of the acid deposition comes from industrial regions in other European countries. What policy approach would be most effective?": "",
  "Banning all automobile traffic within the affected country": "",
  "Building taller smokestacks to disperse pollutants more widely": "",
  "Only treating individual lakes with limestone after they become acidified": "",
  "International agreements requiring emission reductions across borders": "",
  "Because acid rain is a transboundary issue, international cooperation through treaties and agreements is essential. Domestic action alone cannot solve the problem when pollutants originate in other nations.": "",
  "A farmer notices that crop yields have declined over several years. Soil tests reveal low pH, depleted calcium and magnesium, and elevated aluminum levels. The farm is located downwind from several coal-burning power plants. What is the most likely cause of the soil degradation?": "",
  "Excessive irrigation raising the water table": "",
  "Chronic acid deposition leaching nutrients from the soil and mobilizing toxic aluminum": "",
  "Drought conditions reducing mineral availability": "",
  "Overuse of alkaline fertilizers": "",
  "Acid deposition lowers soil pH, causing essential base cations like calcium and magnesium to be leached away while releasing aluminum ions from soil minerals, which damages roots and reduces crop yields.": "",
  "A lake management team decides to add powdered limestone to an acidified lake each year. Fish populations begin to recover, but the team must reapply limestone annually. Why is liming considered a temporary solution rather than a permanent fix?": "",
  "The limestone dissolves too slowly to have any effect": "",
  "Limestone is toxic to fish in large quantities": "",
  "Liming treats the symptoms but does not address the ongoing source of acid deposition": "",
  "Limestone permanently changes the lake's ecosystem": "",
  "Liming neutralizes existing acidity but does not stop new acid deposition from occurring. As long as SO₂ and NOₓ emissions continue, the lake will be re-acidified and require repeated treatment.": "",
  "In a forested mountain region, researchers observe that red spruce trees at high elevations are dying at an alarming rate. The trees show damaged needles, stunted growth, and weakened root systems. Soil analysis reveals very low calcium and high aluminum. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "Logging activity has disrupted the tree root systems": "",
  "Climate change has made the elevation too warm for red spruce": "",
  "The trees are affected by a new fungal disease": "",
  "Acid fog and acid rain at high elevations have depleted soil nutrients and damaged the trees": "",
  "High-elevation forests are especially vulnerable to acid deposition because they are frequently bathed in acidic cloud water and fog. This strips calcium from needles and soil while releasing toxic aluminum that damages roots.": "",
  "After the U.S. Acid Rain Program was implemented in 1995, SO₂ emissions from power plants decreased by approximately 80% by 2015. However, recovery of acidified lakes has been slower than expected. What is the most likely reason for the delayed recovery?": "",
  "Lake organisms adapted to acidic conditions and cannot survive in neutral water": "",
  "New sources of acid rain replaced the old ones": "",
  "The Acid Rain Program was not actually enforced": "",
  "Decades of acid deposition depleted soil buffering minerals, and natural replenishment of these minerals takes many years": "",
  "Years of acid deposition depleted the natural buffering minerals (calcium and magnesium) in watershed soils. Even after emissions decline, it takes decades for weathering processes to replenish these minerals.": "",
  "A country considers building taller smokestacks at its power plants to reduce local air pollution. While local air quality improves, what unintended consequence is most likely?": "",
  "The pollutants are destroyed by ultraviolet light at higher altitudes": "",
  "Total emissions are reduced because the pollutants are diluted": "",
  "Taller stacks capture more pollutants before release": "",
  "Pollutants are dispersed over wider areas, increasing acid deposition in distant regions": "",
  "Taller smokestacks release pollutants higher into the atmosphere where winds can carry them much farther, spreading acid deposition over a wider geographic area rather than reducing total emissions.": "",
  "A community near a large industrial area reports that bronze statues, iron fences, and stone monuments are deteriorating faster than expected. Rain samples collected in the area show a pH of 4.2. What combination of effects is the community experiencing?": "",
  "Accelerated corrosion of metals and chemical weathering of stone caused by acid deposition": "",
  "Normal aging of materials unrelated to air quality": "",
  "Only biological damage to vegetation and wildlife": "",
  "Damage caused solely by high temperatures in the area": "",
  "Acid deposition with a pH of 4.2 is significantly acidic and accelerates both the corrosion of metals like bronze and iron and the chemical weathering of stone, particularly limestone and marble monuments.": ""
}